│ same underlying object is accessed via pointers in different address spaces   │
│ (addrspace(3) and addrspace(4)), triggering a grouping attempt across address │
│ spaces and leading to the assertion failure.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe  │
│ log shows two alias sets: one must-alias set containing %as3 and %as4, and    │
│ another may-alias set containing %dst1.as1 and %dst2.as1. LAA identifies      │
│ runtime check pointers for %as3, %as4, %dst1.as1, and %dst2.as1. During       │
│ groupChecks, groups are built from equivalence classes of dependency          │
│ candidates under the assumption they share underlying objects and thus can be │
│ compared. However, this does not account for differing address spaces.\n\n3.  │
│ Root Cause Analysis:\nRuntimeCheckingPtrGroup stores an AddressSpace value    │
│ initialized from the first member (constructor at lines 181-189). The         │
│ grouping algorithm in groupChecks attempts to add pointers to existing groups │
│ without verifying address space compatibility. When addPointer is called for  │
│ a pointer from a different address space, the assertion AddressSpace == AS    │
│ fails. The assertion is correct; the bug lies in groupChecks failing to       │
│ filter by address space before attempting to merge pointers into a            │
│ group.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nWe should guard the merge in            │
│ groupChecks by checking that the pointer\u2019s address space matches the     │
│ group\u2019s AddressSpace before calling addPointer. This preserves the       │
│ invariant enforced by addPointer and prevents cross-address-space             │
│ grouping.\n\nEdit point:\n- File: llvm/lib/Analysis/LoopAccessAnalysis.cpp\n- │
│ Lines: 540-556\n- Change: Insert an address space compatibility check before  │
│ calling Group.addPointer.\n\nSuggested modification:\nWithin the loop that    │
│ iterates over existing Groups, introduce:\n  unsigned PtrAS =                 │
│ Pointers[Pointer].PointerValue->getType()->getPointerAddressSpace();\n  if    │
│ (Group.AddressSpace != PtrAS)\n    continue; // Skip groups with different    │
│ address spaces.\nThen proceed to TotalComparisons++ and Group.addPointer as   │
│ before. Alternatively, place the TotalComparisons++ after the AS check to     │
│ avoid counting skipped comparisons.\n\nThis ensures we don't attempt to merge │
│ pointers into groups with differing address spaces, maintaining the invariant │
│ and avoiding the assertion.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy preventing                  │
│ cross-address-space grouping in groupChecks, we respect the invariant that a  │
│ RuntimeCheckingPtrGroup contains only pointers from the same address space.   │
│ This resolves the assertion failure when analyzing loops that access the same │
│ underlying object through pointers in different address spaces, such as the   │
│ provided reproducer. The fix is localized to the grouping logic and does not  │
│ alter other aspects of LAA."                                                  │
