│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash occurs during Loop Access Analysis printing, specifically when      │
│ grouping runtime pointer checks. The assertion in                             │
│ RuntimeCheckingPtrGroup::addPointer enforces that all pointers in a group     │
│ must have the same address space. In the provided IR, the same underlying     │
│ object is accessed via pointers in different address spaces (addrspace(3) and │
│ addrspace(4)), triggering a grouping attempt across address spaces and        │
│ leading to the assertion failure.                                             │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The log shows two alias sets: one must-alias set containing %as3 and %as4,    │
│ and another may-alias set containing %dst1.as1 and %dst2.as1. LAA identifies  │
│ runtime check pointers for %as3, %as4, %dst1.as1, and %dst2.as1. During       │
│ groupChecks, groups are built from equivalence classes of dependency          │
│ candidates under the assumption they share underlying objects and thus can be │
│ compared. However, this does not account for differing address spaces.        │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ RuntimeCheckingPtrGroup stores an AddressSpace value initialized from the     │
│ first member (constructor at lines 181-189). The grouping algorithm in        │
│ groupChecks attempts to add pointers to existing groups without verifying     │
│ address space compatibility. When addPointer is called for a pointer from a   │
│ different address space, the assertion AddressSpace == AS fails. The          │
│ assertion is correct; the bug lies in groupChecks failing to filter by        │
│ address space before attempting to merge pointers into a group.               │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ We should guard the merge in groupChecks by checking that the pointer’s       │
│ address space matches the group’s AddressSpace before calling addPointer.     │
│ This preserves the invariant enforced by addPointer and prevents              │
│ cross-address-space grouping.                                                 │
│                                                                               │
│ Edit point:                                                                   │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Analysis/LoopAccessAnalysis.cpp                              │
│ - Lines: 540-556                                                              │
│ - Change: Insert an address space compatibility check before calling          │
│ Group.addPointer.                                                             │
│                                                                               │
│ Suggested modification:                                                       │
│ Within the loop that iterates over existing Groups, introduce:                │
│   unsigned PtrAS =                                                            │
│ Pointers[Pointer].PointerValue->getType()->getPointerAddressSpace();          │
│   if (Group.AddressSpace != PtrAS)                                            │
│     continue; // Skip groups with different address spaces.                   │
│ Then proceed to TotalComparisons++ and Group.addPointer as before.            │
│ Alternatively, place the TotalComparisons++ after the AS check to avoid       │
│ counting skipped comparisons.                                                 │
│                                                                               │
│ This ensures we don't attempt to merge pointers into groups with differing    │
│ address spaces, maintaining the invariant and avoiding the assertion.         │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By preventing cross-address-space grouping in groupChecks, we respect the     │
│ invariant that a RuntimeCheckingPtrGroup contains only pointers from the same │
│ address space. This resolves the assertion failure when analyzing loops that  │
│ access the same underlying object through pointers in different address       │
│ spaces, such as the provided reproducer. The fix is localized to the grouping │
│ logic and does not alter other aspects of LAA.                                │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
